{"title_page": "Sanah Moidutty", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{undisclosed paid|date=February 2019}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=February 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Sanah Moidutty\n| image            = SANAH Live In Concert.png\n| caption          = Sanah Moidutty Live in Concert\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1991|07|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| genre            = Film, Indi Pop, Carnatic, Hindustani, Western\n| occupation       = Singer\n| instrument       = piano\n| years_active     = 2000\u2013present\n}}\n[[File:Sanah Moidutty Official Logo.jpg|thumb|88x88px|Official Logo]]\n'''Sanah Moidutty''' (born 1 July 1991) is an Indian singer songwriter. She sings [[Classical Indian music|Indian classical]], [[pop music]]. She has been trained in [[Carnatic music|Carnatic]] and [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani classical]] music as well as western vocals. In November 2017, she was awarded \"Best Singing Sensation\" for the year 2017 at the Asia Vision Movie Awards 2017 for the song Afeemi from [[Meri Pyaari Bindu]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vijayakar|first1=R.M.|title=Meri Pyaari Bindu' Music Review: Clever Lyrics, Unusual Voices and Retro Tenors Make Melodious Tracks|url=http://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/bollywood/meri-pyaari-bindu-music-review-clever-lyrics-unusual-voices-and/article_7011cc3c-362e-11e7-8176-cb1c0c67d714.html|website=www.indiawest.com|publisher=India West|accessdate=11 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\n\nSanah was born in Mumbai in a Malayali family from Kerala. Sanah started singing at the age of 5 and since wanted to be a singer. Her talent was identified by her mother, who encouraged her to learn music.<ref>{{cite news|last1=M|first1=Athira|title=Sing on Sanah|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/singer-sanah-moidutty-is-on-a-roll/article18390130.ece|accessdate=5 May 2017|publisher=The Hindu|date=5 May 2017}}</ref> She has been trained in Carnatic classical music for 6 years under Sundari Gopalakrishnan, Hindustani classical music for 7 years under Madhuvanti Pethe and Western vocals from [[Samantha Edwards (singer)|Samantha Edwards.]] Sanah was also briefly trained under [[Ghulam Mustafa Khan (singer)|Ustad Ghulam Mustafa Khan]] sahab.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last1=Ghosh|first1=Ananya|title=Sanah Moidutty: The classically trained #coverstars|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/sanah-moidutty-the-classically-trained-coverstars/story-cWemTzZGCW44dojla8sUgK.html|accessdate=6 September 2017|issue=HT Brunch|publisher=Hindustan Times|date=6 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHer first stage show was at the age of 7. In a year's time she started singing with the children's troupe \"Bacchon Ki Duniya\" and few other groups. She did over 500 stage shows with the troupe or solo by the time she turned 18. She stood to be the 1st runner up in [[Hindustan Times]] Voice of Mumbai in 2007.\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Sanah Moidutty at Star of Asia Almati.jpg|thumb|222x222px|Sanah Moidutty at Star of Asia Almati]]\nShe graduated from a computer engineering course in 2013 from St Francis Institute of Technology, Mumbai. In 2011, she got her first break in Bollywood while still pursuing engineering. Sanah was noticed at a talent hunt in college after which she went on to sing for films. In 2012, Sanah decided to start her YouTube channel. She uploaded the first video of her rendition of the song Manmarziyan in 2013. It was recorded at the terrace of her residence and the song got a fair response. This was followed by O Rangrezz from Bhaag Milkha Bhaag. \"Shankar \u2013Ehsaan-Loy, who had composed the original, liked Sanah's version. She also shared the link with AR Rahman who happened to listen to the song and like it. This led to the 3 songs Sanah sang for A R Rahman in the following year.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pandian|first1=Avinash|title=''ANOTHER LIFE JOURNEY STARTED AFTER I MET AR RAHMAN''|url=https://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-16/sanah-moidutty-talks-about-her-working-experience-with-ar-rahman.html|accessdate=6 September 2017|publisher=BehindWoods.com|date=6 September 2017}}</ref> Sanah has rendered her voice in Hindi Films like ''[[Always Kabhi Kabhi]]'', ''[[Gori Tere Pyaar Mein]]'', ''[[The Attacks of 26/11]]'', ''[[24 (2016 film)|24]]'', ''[[Mohenjo Daro (film)|Mohenjo Daro]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Meeting AR Rahman was a dream: Sanah Moidutty|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/160716/meeting-ar-rahman-was-a-dream-sanah-moidutty.html|accessdate=16 July 2016|issue=Entertainment, Music|publisher=Deccan Chronicle|date=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Madhavan|first1=Anusree|title=Meet Sanah Moidutty, the Malayalee voice in Mohenjo Daro|url=http://english.mathrubhumi.com/features/specials/meet-sanah-moidutty-the-malayalee-voice-in-mohenjo-daro-english-news-1.1199978|accessdate=13 July 2016|agency=Mathrubhumi Printing and Publishing Company Limited|issue=Specials|publisher=Matrabhumi|date=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Team|first1=RnM|title=I fell in love with music because of AR Rahman: Sanah Moidutty|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/entertainment/editorial/news/171205-i-fell-love-music-because-ar-rahman-sanah|accessdate=5 December 2017|publisher=Radio & Music|date=5 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Yours sincerely, Sanah Moidutty|url=https://mad-garage.com/yours-sincerely-sanah-moidutty/|accessdate=2 April 2017|agency=Mad Garage|publisher=Mad Garage|date=2 April 2017}}</ref> Her popularity in the film industry & YouTube is on a rise ever since.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/meet-the-social-media-sensations-who-are-reinventing-bollywood-classics-coverstars/story-AcEk7j7G4IXcUglgs5K6pK.html|title=Meet the social media sensations who are reinventing Bollywood classics #coverstars|last=Ghosh|first=Ananya|date=3 September 2017|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe has also sung for ad films like Cinthol and Eva deos. An episode of the musical TV show Sound Trek features Sanah with Achint Thakkar on [[Fox Life]] where they recreate a 70's Bollywood song \"KITNA PYAARA VAADA HAI\". In 2016 Sanah was also commissioned to create a cover of \"Counting Stars\" for the Bombay Festival. She actively releases music on her YouTube Channel in her name. The Malyalam Renditions released by Sanah have been very well received.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Madhukalya|first1=Anwesha|title=10 Indian Origin Singers On YouTube Who'll Make You Listen To Them On Loop|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/08/10/10-indian-origin-singers-on-youtube_a_21448730/|website=www.huffingtonpost.in|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Soman|first1=Deepa|title=I always felt a connect with old Malayalam songs: Sanah Moidutty|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/music/i-always-felt-a-connect-with-old-malayalam-songs-sanah-moidutty/articleshow/61269639.cms|accessdate=28 October 2017|issue=Entertainment|publisher=Times of India|date=28 October 2017}}</ref>  She has done Live shows across the globe, solo as well as with [[Vishal\u2013Shekhar|Vishal Shekhar]], [[Sanam (band)|Band SANAM]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Features|first1=Express|title=Drenched in the Monsoon Music Mania|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Drenched-in-the-Monsoon-Music-Mania/2014/11/17/article2526320.ece|accessdate=17 November 2014|agency=Express Publications (Madurai) Limited|issue=Chennai|publisher=New Indian Express|date=17 November 2014}}</ref> [[Keerthi Sagathia]]  and [[Ash King]]. The multilingual singer can confidently sing in English, Hindi, Marathi, Tamil, Malyalam, Telugu, Bengali, Punjabi, Gujarati and Kannada. As a part of Jammin, a digital music collaboration, Sanah has done a collaboration called \"Ishq Abhi Bhi\" with Bollywood composer [[Clinton Cerejo]], and a collaboration called \"Yaara\" composed by [[A R Rahman]].\n\nIn 2017, Sanah Moidutty performed at across the world including Almaty Kazakhstan at a two-day \"Star of Asia\" international festival that had the best, voices, sounds and rhythms from the Asian region.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spindler|first1=Wolfgang|title=Star of Asia Festival shines a light on regional music|url=http://www.euronews.com/2017/08/28/star-of-asia-festival-shines-a-light-on-regional-music|accessdate=28 August 2017|publisher=Euro News|date=28 August 2017}}</ref> She is currently learning Hindustani classical with Sunil Borgaonkar Ji. \n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Filmography ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! YEAR !! SONG (s) !! ALBUM !! COMPOSER (s) !! CO SINGERS\n|-\n| 2011 ||[[Always Kabhi Kabhi]]- Title Track ||[[Always Kabhi Kabhi]]  ([[Red Chillies Entertainment|A Red Chillies Production]] ) || Shree D and Ashish Rego || Bhavin Dhanak\n|-\n|2013 || Moto Ghotalo ||[[Gori Tere Pyaar Mein]] (Dharma Productions) ||[[Vishal-Shekhar]]||[[Sukhwinder Singh]]\n|-\n| 2013 || Raghupati Raghav ||[[The Attacks of 26/11|Attacks of 26/11]] (An Alumbra Entertainment Production) || Vishal R. Khosla || Chorus\n|-\n| 2016 || Mei Nigara (Tamil)<ref>{{cite news|title=Mei Nigara|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/mei-nigara/article8562143.ece|accessdate=6 May 2016|agency=The Hindu|issue=Friday Review|publisher=The Hindu|date=6 May 2016}}</ref>||[[24 (2016 film)|24]] [A [[2D Entertainment|2 D entertainment production]]||[[A R Rahman]]||[[Sid Sriram]], [[Jonita Gandhi]]\n|-\n| 2016 || Manasuke (Telugu)<ref>{{cite news|last1=TNN|first1=Times News Network|title=24 tracklist is here|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/music/24-tracklist-is-here/articleshow/51725152.cms|accessdate=7 April 2016|issue=Entertainment|publisher=Times Of India|dat