{"title_page": "Bangabasi College", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}{{Not to be confused with|Bangabasi Morning College|Bangabasi Evening College|Bangabasi College of Commerce}}{{Infobox university\n| image_name = Bangabasi_College.jpg\n| motto = ''\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0923\u093f\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0924\u0947\u0928 \u092a\u0930\u093f\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0936\u0928\u0947\u0928 \u0938\u0947\u0935\u092f\u093e''\n| motto_lang = Sanskrit\n| name = Bangabasi College\n| mottoeng = Earn Education & Serve the Humanitarian\n| established = 27 November 1887\n| type = Public\n| academic_affiliation = [[University of Calcutta]]\n| address = 19, Rajkumar Chakraborty Sarani\n| city = [[Kolkata]]\n| state = [[West Bengal]]\n| postalcode = 700009\n| country = [[India]]\n| campus = Urban, 0.60 acres\n| language = [[English language|English]] and [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| sports = Bangabasi College Athletic Club\n| president = Sri Ashok Kumar Deb\n| principal = Dr. Subrata Sankar Bagchi\n| students = 2570 + 410 (self-funded)\n| undergrad = 2550\n| postgrad = 20\n| website = {{url|http://bangabasi.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Bangabasi College''' is a [[Kolkata]]-based [[liberal arts college|liberal arts, commerce and sciences college]].<ref>http://www.lawsofindia.org/pdf/west_bengal/1978/1978WB72.pdf</ref> It offers undergraduate and postgraduate courses of the [[University of Calcutta]]. It was founded by [[Girish Chandra Bose]], an educationist, social reformer and agriculturist, in 1887.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bangabasi College Centenary Commemoration Volume|chapter=Our Founder|url=https://bangabasi-opac.l2c2.co.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=25517|location=Calcutta|publisher=Bangabasi College|year=1987}}</ref> It was the first nationalist college. It played a major role in Disobedience Movement of 1930 and sacrifice of Shri Jatindra Nath Das, an undergraduate student of the college The college celebrated its 125th anniversary from November 2011 to October 2012. It has been accredited by the [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]] of India (NAAC) with \"B\" certificate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://naacindia.org/Colleges.asp?state%3D26 |accessdate=3 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011091149/http://naacindia.org/Colleges.asp?state=26 |archivedate=11 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Girish Chandra Bose|Acharya Girish Chandra Bose]] founded an institution, named Bangabasi School, in a rented house in [[Bowbazar Street]] with six teachers and twelve students in the year 1885. Two years later, the college was established with private management, under the inspiration and guidance of [[Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar]]. It started with F.A. course and slowly obtained affiliation for the [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]], [[Bachelor of Laws|B.L.]] and [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] courses to meet the requirements of the college.\n\nIn 1930. the college moved into its present premises at 19, Scott Lane (now Raj Kumar Chakraborty Sarani). Honours course in various subjects were introduced.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangabasi.ac.in/en/history-of-the-college|title=Bangabasi College {{!}} History of the College|website=www.bangabasi.ac.in|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> During the [[World War II]] another branch of the college was established in [[Kushtia]] (now in [[Bangladesh]]) in 1942, as the people of Kolkata were troubled by the bombing of Japanese troops. After the [[World War II]] it was closed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangabasievening.edu.in/home/anecdotes|title=Bangabasi {{!}} Home|website=www.bangabasievening.edu.in|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> After Independence in 1947, the college started to see receive huge admissions and thus it created extra-pressure on the existing infrastructure and system. To cope up with the demand, college was divided in morning and evening sections and Acharya Girish Chandra Bose started a new evening section only for commerce. Later in 1964, it emerged as Bangabasi College of Commerce (renamed as [[Acharya Girish Chandra Bose College]] in 2005).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThrough phase reduction scheme of the [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commission]] (UGC), the shifts were separated and two new colleges, i.e. Bangabasi Morning College and Bangabasi Evening College emerged in the same building and Bangabasi College of Commerce in a separate building on 11th April, 1965.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agcbosecollege.org/#openModal|title=Acharya Girish Chandra Bose College - The Official Website|website=www.agcbosecollege.org|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> With this, four colleges came up; '''Bangabasi College,  Bangabasi Morning College, Bangabasi Evening College and Bangabasi College of Commerce.''' In 1979 Bangabasi College opened its own Commerce Department, and also became [[Mixed-sex education|co-ed]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://bangabasi.ac.in/assets/myos_editor/fileman/Uploads/prospectus_compressed.pdf|title=Bangabasi College : Prospectus|last=|first=|date=December 16, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Courses ==\nCourses listed below are undergraduate, except zoology. Only zoology department has both undergraduate and postgraduate courses.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangabasi.ac.in/|title=Bangabasi College {{!}} Bangabasi College Home Page|website=www.bangabasi.ac.in|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangabasi.ac.in/en/introduction-to-the-department-of-zoology|title=Bangabasi College {{!}} Introduction to the department [Zoology]|website=www.bangabasi.ac.in|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Language and Literature ===\n\n* [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n* [[English language|English]]\n* [[Hindi]]\n* [[Sanskrit]]\n\n=== Social Science ===\n\n* [[Economics]]\n* [[Education]]\n* [[Geography]]\n* [[History]]\n* [[Philosophy]]\n* [[Political science|Political Science]]\n* [[Psychology]]\n* [[Sociology]]\n\n=== Commerce ===\n\n* [[Commerce]]\n\n=== Pure Science ===\n\n* [[Chemistry]]\n* [[Computer science|Computer Science]]\n* [[Mathematics]]\n* [[Physics]]\n\n=== Biological Science ===\n\n* [[Anthropology]]\n* [[Botany]]\n* [[Zoology]]\n\n[[Image:agcbmemo.JPG|thumb|Late Acharya Girish Chandra Bose memorial]]\n\n== Postgraduate studies ==\nPostgraduate studies started in Zoology in 2005, under the semester system (CBCS), Department of Zoology, [[University of Calcutta]].\n\nRecently, it was acknowledged by the [[Department of Science and Technology (India)|Department of Science and Technology]], by sanctioning a grants-in-aid to the extent of Rs,20,00,000 for procuring modern equipment and adequate software support.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Department timeline<ref name=\":3\" />\n!Year\n!Department\n!Note\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1885\n|[[Mathematics]]\n|Honours course in 1940\n|-\n|[[Philosophy]]\n|Honours course in 1944\n|-\n|[[Physics]]\n|Honours course in 1950\n|-\n|1910\n|[[Economics]]\n|Honours course in 1950\n|-\n|1930\n|[[History]]\n|Honours course in 2000\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1934\n|[[English language|English]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Sanskrit]]\n|\n|-\n|1936\n|[[Anthropology]]\n|Degree General course started in 1950 and Honours course in 1978\n|-\n|1939\n|[[Botany]]\n|Started with intermediate, Degree and Masters Course, but later discontinued. Honours course started in 1995\n|-\n|1944\n|[[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n|Supported the nationalist movement for independence\n|-\n|1950\n|[[Chemistry]]\n|\n|-\n|1955\n|[[Zoology]]\n|M.Sc. started in 2005\n|-\n|1957\n|[[Political science|Political Science]]\n|\n|-\n|1965\n|[[Hindi]]\n|Minor department with only one full time faculty member\n|-\n|1979\n|[[Commerce]]\n|Own commerce department\n|-\n|1996\n|[[Computer science|Computer Science]]\n|Honours course in 2003\n|-\n|2003\n|[[Geography]]\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|[[Sociology]]\n|Honours course in 2008\n|-\n|2006\n|[[Psychology]]\n|As a subsidiary subject in 2006 and in 2007\n|-\n|2007\n|[[Education]]\n|Newest department\n|}\n\n== Facilities ==\n\n=== Student service cell ===\n\n* Student support cell\n* Placement cell\n* Counselling cell\n* Women's cell\n* Anti-ragging cell\n* Grievance redressal cell\n* Equal opportunity cell\n\n=== Academic ===\n\n* [[Laboratories]]\n* [[Internet]] and [[Wifi|WiFi]]\n* Educational tours\n* Scholarships\n\n=== Infrastructural ===\n\n* Cheap canteen\n* Auditorium\n* Common room\n* Gymnasium\n* Drinking water\n* Playground\n* Safety and first-aid\n\n== Other activities ==\n\n* NSS\n* Sports and Games\n* Assembly\n* Prize distribution\n* Students fair\n* Cultural activities\n* Computer skill development\n* Self defense\n\n== Notable alumni ==\nThe alumni of Bangabasi College have achieved prominence in various fields. Following is the list of notable alumni of this college.\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order by LAST NAME \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n*[[Chitta Basu (director)|Chitta Basu]], film director of Bengal during the sixties\n*[[Salil Chowdhury]], music composer\n*[[Jatindra Nath Das]], Indian independence activist, revolutionary and martyr.\n*[[Sudhi Ranjan Das]], [[Chief Justice of India]]\n*[[Bishnu Dey]], poet; winner of [[Jnanpith Award]]\n*[[Tushar Kanti Ghosh]], recipient of [[Padma Bhushan]], former editor, [[Amrita Bazar Patrika]]\n*[[Pankaj Gupta]], {{post-nominals|MBE}}, sports administrator\n*[[Kansari Halder]],  Indian politician\n*[[Baby Islam]],  Indian and Bangladeshi cinematographer and film director\n*[[A. T. Kovoor]], professor, rationalist\n*[[Swami Lokeshwarananda]], monk of the [[Ramakrishna Mission]]\n*[[Chittabrata Majumdar]], general secretary of [[Centre of Indian Trade Unions|CITU]]\n*[[Sreela Majumdar]], actress\n*[[Indumadhab Mallick]], Indian polymath who invented the ICMIC cooker\n*[[Ashesh Prosad Mitra]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society]], former director general, [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research|CSIR]]<ref>Peer Team Report on the Institutional Assessment<!--SIC--> and Accreditation of Bangabasi College. March 16\u201318, 2007. NAAC. {{cite web|url=http://naacindia.org/Reports/217%20Bangabasi%20College,%20WB.doc |accessdate=3 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518072457/http://naacindia.org/Reports/217%20Bangabasi%20College%2C%20WB.doc |archivedate=18 May 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[Anantahari Mitra]], Indian freedom fighter and martyr\n*[[Bimal Mukherjee]], globe-trotter on bicycle\n*[[Subrata Mukherjee]], politician, Minister\n*[[Rasikendra Nath Nandi]], social reformer\n*[[Baishnab Charan Parida]], politician, writer and social activist\n*[[Chittaranjan Saha]], Bangladeshi educationist, was awarded [[Ekushey Padak]]\n*[[Amal Kumar Sarkar]], chief Justice of India\n*[[Dwijesh Chandra Sen]],  freedom fighter\n*[[Benudhar Sharma]], recipient of [[Padma Bhushan]] and [[Sahitya Akademi Award]], President of [[Assam Sahitya Sabha]]\n*[[Swami Yatiswarananda]], vice-president of [[Ramakrishna Order]] whose headquarter is in Belur Math\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order by LAST NAME \u2666\u2666\u2666--->\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Bangabasi Morning College]]\n*[[Bangabasi Evening College]]\n*[[Bangabasi College of Commerce]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official}}\n\n{{coord|22.5693|88.3683|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n\n{{Calcutta University}}\n{{Bengal Renaissance}}\n\n[[Category:Academic institutions associated with the Bengal Renaissance]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta affiliates]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}{{Not to be confused with|Bangabasi Morning College|Bangabasi Evening College|Bangabasi College of Commerce}}{{Infobox university\n| image_name = Bangabasi_College.jpg\n| motto = ''\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0923\u093f\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0924\u0947\u0928 \u092a\u0930\u093f\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0936\u0928\u0947\u0928 \u0938\u0947\u0935\u092f\u093e''\n| motto_lang = Sanskrit\n| name = Bangabasi College\n| mottoeng = Earn Education & Serve the Humanitarian\n| established = 27 November 1887\n| type = Public\n| academic_affiliation = [[University of Calcutta]]\n| address = 19, Rajkumar Chakraborty Sarani\n| city = [[Kolkata]]\n| state = [[West Bengal]]\n| postalcode = 700009\n| country = [[India]]\n| campus = Urban, 0.60 acres\n| language = [[English language|English]] and [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| sports = Bangabasi College Athletic Club\n| president = Sri Ashok Kumar Deb\n| principal = Dr. Subrata Sankar Bagchi\n| students = 2570 + 410 (self-funded)\n| undergrad = 2550\n| postgrad = 20\n| website = {{url|http://bangabasi.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Bangabasi College''' is a [[Kolkata]]-based [[liberal arts college|liberal arts, commerce and sciences college]].<ref>http://www.lawsofindia.org/pdf/west_bengal/1978/1978WB72.pdf</ref> It offers undergraduate and postgraduate courses of the [[University of Calcutta]]. It was founded by [[Girish Chandra Bose]], an educationist, social reformer and agriculturist, in 1887.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bangabasi College Centenary Commemoration Volume|chapter=Our Founder|url=https://bangabasi-opac.l2c2.co.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=25517|location=Calcutta|publisher=Bangabasi College|year=1987}}</ref> It was the first nationalist college. It played a major role in Disobedience Movement of 1930 and sacrifice of Shri Jatindra Nath Das, an undergraduate student of the college The college celebrated its 125th anniversary from November 2011 to October 2012. It has been accredited by the [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]] of India (NAAC) with \"B\" certificate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://naacindia.org/Colleges.asp?state%3D26 |accessdate=3 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011091149/http://naacindia.org/Colleges.asp?state=26 |archivedate=11 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Girish Chandra Bose|Acharya Girish Chandra Bose]] founded an institution, named Bangabasi School, in a rented house in [[Bowbazar Street]] with six teachers and twelve students in the year 1885. Two years later, the college was established with private management, under the inspiration and guidance of [[Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar]]. It started with F.A. course and slowly obtained affiliation for the [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]], [[Bachelor of Laws|B.L.]] and [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] courses to meet the requirements of the college.\n\nIn 1930. the college moved into its present premises at 19, Scott Lane (now Raj Kumar Chakraborty Sarani). Honours course in various subjects were introduced.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangabasi.ac.in/en/history-of-the-college|title=Bangabasi College {{!}} History of the College|website=www.bangabasi.ac.in|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> During the [[World War II]] another branch of the college was established in [[Kushtia]] (now in [[Bangladesh]]) in 1942, as the people of Kolkata were troubled by the bombing of Japanese troops. After the [[World War II]] it was closed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangabasievening.edu.in/home/anecdotes|title=Bangabasi {{!}} Home|website=www.bangabasievening.edu.in|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> After Independence in 1947, the college started to see receive huge admissions and thus it created extra-pressure on the existing infrastructure and system. To cope up with the demand, college was divided in morning and evening sections and Acharya Girish Chandra Bose started a new evening section only for commerce. Later in 1964, it emerged as Bangabasi College of Commerce (renamed as [[Acharya Girish Chandra Bose College]] in 2005).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThrough phase reduction scheme of the [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commission]] (UGC), the shifts were separated and two new colleges, i.e. Bangabasi Morning College and Bangabasi Evening College emerged in the same building and Bangabasi College of Commerce in a separate building on 11th April, 1965.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agcbosecollege.org/#openModal|title=Acharya Girish Chandra Bose College - The Official Website|website=www.agcbosecollege.org|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> With this, four colleges came up; '''Bangabasi College,  Bangabasi Morning College, Bangabasi Evening College and Bangabasi College of Commerce.''' In 1979 Bangabasi College opened its own Commerce Department, and also became [[Mixed-sex education|co-ed]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://bangabasi.ac.in/assets/myos_editor/fileman/Uploads/prospectus_compressed.pdf|title=Bangabasi College : Prospectus|last=|first=|date=December 16, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Courses ==\nCourses listed below are undergraduate, except zoology. Only zoology department has both undergraduate and postgraduate courses.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangabasi.ac.in/|title=Bangabasi College {{!}} Bangabasi College Home Page|website=www.bangabasi.ac.in|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangabasi.ac.in/en/introduction-to-the-department-of-zoology|title=Bangabasi College {{!}} Introduction to the department [Zoology]|website=www.bangabasi.ac.in|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Language and Literature ===\n\n* [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n* [[English language|English]]\n* [[Hindi]]\n* [[Sanskrit]]\n\n=== Social Science ===\n\n* [[Economics]]\n* [[Education]]\n* [[Geography]]\n* [[History]]\n* [[Philosophy]]\n* [[Political science|Political Science]]\n* [[Psychology]]\n* [[Sociology]]\n\n=== Commerce ===\n\n* [[Commerce]]\n\n=== Pure Science ===\n\n* [[Chemistry]]\n* [[Computer science|Computer Science]]\n* [[Mathematics]]\n* [[Physics]]\n\n=== Biological Science ===\n\n* [[Anthropology]]\n* [[Botany]]\n* [[Zoology]]\n\n[[Image:agcbmemo.JPG|thumb|Late Acharya Girish Chandra Bose memorial]]\n\n== Postgraduate studies ==\nPostgraduate studies started in Zoology in 2005, under the semester system (CBCS), Department of Zoology, [[University of Calcutta]].\n\nRecently, it was acknowledged by the [[Department of Science and Technology (India)|Department of Science and Technology]], by sanctioning a grants-in-aid to the extent of Rs,20,00,000 for procuring modern equipment and adequate software support.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Department timeline<ref name=\":3\" />\n!Year\n!Department\n!Note\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1885\n|[[Mathematics]]\n|Honours course in 1940\n|-\n|[[Philosophy]]\n|Honours course in 1944\n|-\n|[[Physics]]\n|Honours course in 1950\n|-\n|1910\n|[[Economics]]\n|Honours course in 1950\n|-\n|1930\n|[[History]]\n|Honours course in 2000\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1934\n|[[English language|English]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Sanskrit]]\n|\n|-\n|1936\n|[[Anthropology]]\n|Degree General course started in 1950 and Honours course in 1978\n|-\n|1939\n|[[Botany]]\n|Started with intermediate, Degree and Masters Course, but later discontinued. Honours course started in 1995\n|-\n|1944\n|[[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n|Supported the nationalist movement for independence\n|-\n|1950\n|[[Chemistry]]\n|\n|-\n|1955\n|[[Zoology]]\n|M.Sc. started in 2005\n|-\n|1957\n|[[Political science|Political Science]]\n|\n|-\n|1965\n|[[Hindi]]\n|Minor department with only one full time faculty member\n|-\n|1979\n|[[Commerce]]\n|Own commerce department\n|-\n|1996\n|[[Computer science|Computer Science]]\n|Honours course in 2003\n|-\n|2003\n|[[Geography]]\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|[[Sociology]]\n|Honours course in 2008\n|-\n|2006\n|[[Psychology]]\n|As a subsidiary subject in 2006 and in 2007\n|-\n|2007\n|[[Education]]\n|Newest department\n|}\n\n== Facilities ==\n\n=== Student service cell ===\n\n* Student support cell\n* Placement cell\n* Counselling cell\n* Women's cell\n* Anti-ragging cell\n* Grievance redressal cell\n* Equal opportunity cell\n\n=== Academic ===\n\n* [[Laboratories]]\n* [[Internet]] and [[Wifi|WiFi]]\n* Educational tours\n* Scholarships\n\n=== Infrastructural ===\n\n* Cheap canteen\n* Auditorium\n* Common room\n* Gymnasium\n* Drinking water\n* Playground\n* Safety and first-aid\n\n== Other activities ==\n\n* NSS\n* Sports and Games\n* Assembly\n* Prize distribution\n* Students fair\n* Cultural activities\n* Computer skill development\n* Self defense\n\n== Notable alumni ==\nThe alumni of Bangabasi College have achieved prominence in various fields. Following is the list of notable alumni of this college.\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order by LAST NAME \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n*[[Chitta Basu (director)|Chitta Basu]], film director of Bengal during the sixties\n*[[Salil Chowdhury]], music composer\n*[[Jatindra Nath Das]], Indian independence activist, revolutionary and martyr.\n*[[Sudhi Ranjan Das]], [[Chief Justice of India]]\n*[[Bishnu Dey]], poet; winner of [[Jnanpith Award]]\n*[[Tushar Kanti Ghosh]], recipient of [[Padma Bhushan]], former editor, [[Amrita Bazar Patrika]]\n*[[Pankaj Gupta]], [[MBE]], sports administrator\n*[[Kansari Halder]],  Indian politician\n*[[Baby Islam]],  Indian and Bangladeshi cinematographer and film director\n*[[A. T. Kovoor]], professor, rationalist\n*[[Swami Lokeshwarananda]], monk of the [[Ramakrishna Mission]]\n*[[Chittabrata Majumdar]], general secretary of [[Centre of Indian Trade Unions|CITU]]\n*[[Sreela Majumdar]], actress\n*[[Indumadhab Mallick]], Indian polymath who invented the ICMIC cooker\n*[[Ashesh Prosad Mitra]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society]], former director general, [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research|CSIR]]<ref>Peer Team Report on the Institutional Assessment<!--SIC--> and Accreditation of Bangabasi College. March 16\u201318, 2007. NAAC. {{cite web|url=http://naacindia.org/Reports/217%20Bangabasi%20College,%20WB.doc |accessdate=3 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518072457/http://naacindia.org/Reports/217%20Bangabasi%20College%2C%20WB.doc |archivedate=18 May 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[Anantahari Mitra]], Indian freedom fighter and martyr\n*[[Bimal Mukherjee]], globe-trotter on bicycle\n*[[Subrata Mukherjee]], politician, Minister\n*[[Rasikendra Nath Nandi]], social reformer\n*[[Baishnab Charan Parida]], politician, writer and social activist\n*[[Chittaranjan Saha]], Bangladeshi educationist, was awarded [[Ekushey Padak]]\n*[[Amal Kumar Sarkar]], chief Justice of India\n*[[Dwijesh Chandra Sen]],  freedom fighter\n*[[Benudhar Sharma]], recipient of [[Padma Bhushan]] and [[Sahitya Akademi Award]], President of [[Assam Sahitya Sabha]]\n*[[Swami Yatiswarananda]], vice-president of [[Ramakrishna Order]] whose headquarter is in Belur Math\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order by LAST NAME \u2666\u2666\u2666--->\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Bangabasi Morning College]]\n*[[Bangabasi Evening College]]\n*[[Bangabasi College of Commerce]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official}}\n\n{{coord|22.5693|88.3683|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n\n{{Calcutta University}}\n{{Bengal Renaissance}}\n\n[[Category:Academic institutions associated with the Bengal Renaissance]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta affiliates]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Paradoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangabasi_College"}
{"title_page": "45th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 45 Street\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = black\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| image = 45th Street - Northbound Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = Manhattan bound platform\n| address = 45th Street &amp; [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]]<br>Brooklyn, NY 11220<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn|Sunset Park]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|38|58.01|N|74|0|33.77|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth south local\n| service_header = Fourth south local header\n| connection = {{Bus icon}} '''[[New York City Transit buses|New York City Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4 (2 in regular service)\n| code = 033\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}<ref name=\"Station Opening\" />\n| wifi = yes\n| passengers = 2,251,921<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -5.8\n| rank = 207<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=36th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth south local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | station=53rd Street | service=Fourth south local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n\n'''45th Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at 45th Street and [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]] in [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] train also stops here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe 45th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 45th Street started on March 15, 1913, and was completed in 1915. The station opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The platforms were lengthened in 1925 and again during a renovation in 1968\u20131970.\n\n== History ==\n===Construction and opening===\nThe 45th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> In 1912, during the Dual System negotiations, the construction of an extension of the Fourth Avenue subway from 43rd Street to 89th Street, just south of the [[86th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|86th Street station]], was recommended. The proposal was approved by the Board of Estimate on February 15, 1912. The PSC directed its chief engineer to create plans on June 14, 1912. The two contracts for the extension, Route 11B, were awarded on September 16, 1912, to Degnon Construction Company for a combined $3.8 million (equivalent to ${{inflation|fmt=c|index=US|value=3.8|start_year=1912|r=1}} million in {{inflation/year|index=US}}).<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nConstruction on Route 11B1, the section of the extension between 43rd Street and 61st Street, which includes the 45th Street station, began on March 15, 1913. Originally, this section was planned to have two tracks, but after the connection to the Sea Beach Line was added to the plan during the middle of construction, the plan was changed to four tracks. This section was completed in 1915.<ref name=\":12\" /> 45th Street opened on June 22, 1915, as part of an extension of the subway to [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue station|Coney Island]], which included the Fourth Avenue Line north of [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]] as well as the entire [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach Line]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Cudahy | first=Brian J. | title=How We Got to Coney Island: The Development of Mass Transportation in Brooklyn and Kings County | publisher=Fordham University Press | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-8232-2211-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cJGUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA218 | access-date=April 24, 2020 | pages=217-218}}</ref><ref name=\"Station Opening\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, 45th Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|490|feet|meters|abbr=}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Legislature|first=New York (State)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ugaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA100&dq=%22union+street%22+LENGTHENING&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8_PLm7tboAhXBhOAKHVx0AzwQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20LENGTHENING&f=false|title=Second Annual Report of the Transit Commission (For the Calendar Year 1922)|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Though the Transit Commission ordered the BMT to lengthen these platforms in September 1923, progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=February 26, 1926|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=March 18, 1926|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1960s ====\nIn the 1960s, the New York City Transit Authority (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 45th Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between this station and [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street station|Bay Ridge\u201495th Street]] on May 3, 1968.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHBIAQAAIAAJ&q=|title=Engineering News-record|date=1968|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=75|language=en}}</ref><!-- The information on the contract bid is likelyin the 1968 Volume of Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation, but this has not been digitized.-->\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended {{Convert|85|feet|meters|abbr=}}<ref name=\":1\" /> to the north,<ref name=\":2\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Line, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=February 21, 1970|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 7, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Station layout==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=36th Street\n|l1=36 St\n|2=53rd Street\n|l2=53 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=315\n}}\n}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout BMT Fourth Avenue Line|prev2=36th Street|next2=53rd Street}}\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s. The R stops here at all times;<ref name=\"ttr\">{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref> some rush-hour W trains stop here in the peak direction;<ref name=\"ttw\">{{NYCS const|timetable|w}}</ref> and the N stops here during late nights, but uses the center express tracks to bypass the station during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref> The platforms are offset as the northbound platform extends further north than the southbound one.<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook3}}</ref>\n\nColumns run along the entire length of both platforms and are painted dark blue. Every other column has a \"45 Street\" sign on it in black with white text. All are round except for the ones near the staircases to the station's main entrance, which was where the platforms were extended in 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r13.jpg|title=A view down the Bay Ridge-bound side platform at 45 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> These columns are I-beams.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r21.jpg|title=Looking down the Bay Ridge-bound platform at 45 Street, this portion must be part of the area added when the platform was extended since it has I-beams all along it.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=October 1, 2012|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> Since the renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain gray-painted cinderblock tiles. The gray cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r1.jpg|title=A 45 Street platform sign, text and an arrow for the only exit to 45 St painted beneath it.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear|left}}[[File:45th St BMT stair jeh.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Eastern street stair]]\n\n===Exits===\nThe station's main entrance is a [[mezzanine (architecture)|mezzanine]] above the platforms and tracks at the north end. It has two staircases to the Manhattan-bound platform<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r24.jpg|title=Looking across to the offset Manhattan-bound platform and the two staircases it has to the mezzanine|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=October 1, 2012|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> and one to the Bay Ridge-bound one at the extreme south end,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r5.jpg|title=Approaching the single staircase up to street level from the Bay Ridge-bound platform at 45 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> a waiting area that allows a free transfer between directions, [[turnstile]] bank, token booth, and two staircases to the northern corners of 45th Street and 4th Avenue.<ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref> The mezzanine contains some of the original mosaic directional and arrow signs. The one by the staircases to the southbound platform says \"Down Town trains\" while the one by the Manhattan-bound platform staircases says \"Up Town Trains.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r7.jpg|title=A mosaic sign for Up Town trains above a modern To 95 Street R sign at 45 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r9.jpg|title=A Down Town Trains mosaic above a modern Manhattan & Queens R sign on the mezzanine at 45 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe southbound platform formerly had an exit-only at the center that led to 46th Street. Evidence of this includes a gated door on the platform wall and adjacent \"EXIT\" signs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r19.jpg|title=A close up of partially painted over text for the now closed exit to 46 St.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r18.jpg|title=A gated door where a high exit turnstile to 46 Street used to leave the Bay Ridge-bound platform from.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The northwest corner exit was closed after it was accidentally destroyed by nearby construction workers. On May 16, 1979, Community Board 7 held a meeting to determine whether residents wanted the entrance closed.<ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26222806/daily_news/|title=Public Hearing|last=|first=|date=May 14, 1979|work=New York Daily News|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The board's chairman cited crime as a reason to close the entrance. The New York City Transit Authority promised to comply with the wish of the board, and the entrance was closed.<ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26223211/daily_news/|title=Express Ideas on BMT Station|last=|first=|date=May 14, 1979|work=New York Daily News|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|45th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:262|BMT 4th Avenue|45th Street}}\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150113014240/http://www.stationreporter.net/rtrain.htm R Train]\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/index.php 45th Street Pictures]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.649322,-74.009721&spn=0,0.013314&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.649393,-74.009652&panoid=xaDl-Fa-Y0P2G9iP_BWMHQ&cbp=12,326.9,,0,9.86 45th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6492729,-74.0095825,3a,75y,98.46h,89.75t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s-dGaQtrQutyc%2FWG3KMnRZW4I%2FAAAAAAAAYWA%2FfSN1j1gWg7AwQffylXaJ01uYxVCM8Jw4QCLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2F-dGaQtrQutyc%2FWG3KMnRZW4I%2FAAAAAAAAYWA%2FfSN1j1gWg7AwQffylXaJ01uYxVCM8Jw4QCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:45th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sunset Park, Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 45 Street\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = black\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| image = 45th Street - Northbound Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = Manhattan bound platform\n| address = 45th Street &amp; [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]]<br>Brooklyn, NY 11220<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn|Sunset Park]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|38|58.01|N|74|0|33.77|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth south local\n| service_header = Fourth south local header\n| connection = {{Bus icon}} '''[[New York City Transit buses|New York City Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4 (2 in regular service)\n| code = 033\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}<ref name=\"Station Opening\" />\n| wifi = yes\n| passengers = 2,251,921<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -5.8\n| rank = 207<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=36th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth south local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | station=53rd Street | service=Fourth south local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n\n'''45th Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at 45th Street and [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]] in [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] train also stops here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe 45th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 45th Street started on March 15, 1913, and was completed in 1915. The station opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The platforms were lengthened in 1925 and again during a renovation in 1968\u20131970.\n\n== History ==\n===Construction and opening===\nThe 45th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> In 1912, during the Dual System negotiations, the construction of an extension of the Fourth Avenue subway from 43rd Street to 89th Street, just south of the [[86th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|86th Street station]], was recommended. The proposal was approved by the Board of Estimate on February 15, 1912. The PSC directed its chief engineer to create plans on June 14, 1912. The two contracts for the extension, Route 11B, were awarded on September 16, 1912, to Degnon Construction Company for a combined $3.8 million (equivalent to ${{inflation|fmt=c|index=US|value=3.8|start_year=1912|r=1}} million in {{inflation/year|index=US}}).<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nConstruction on Route 11B1, the section of the extension between 43rd Street and 61st Street, which includes the 45th Street station, began on March 15, 1913. Originally, this section was planned to have two tracks, but after the connection to the Sea Beach Line was added to the plan during the middle of construction, the plan was changed to four tracks. This section was completed in 1915.<ref name=\":12\" /> 45th Street opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, 45th Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|490|feet|meters|abbr=}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Legislature|first=New York (State)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ugaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA100&dq=%22union+street%22+LENGTHENING&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8_PLm7tboAhXBhOAKHVx0AzwQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20LENGTHENING&f=false|title=Second Annual Report of the Transit Commission (For the Calendar Year 1922)|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}). The BMT had been ordered by the Transit Commission to lengthen these platforms since September 1923.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=February 26, 1926|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=March 18, 1926|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1960s ====\nIn the 1960s, the New York City Transit Authority (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 45th Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between this station and [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street station|Bay Ridge\u201495th Street]] on May 3, 1968.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHBIAQAAIAAJ&q=|title=Engineering News-record|date=1968|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=75|language=en}}</ref><!-- The information on the contract bid is likelyin the 1968 Volume of Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation, but this has not been digitized.-->\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended {{Convert|85|feet|meters|abbr=}}<ref name=\":1\" /> to the north,<ref name=\":2\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Line, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=February 21, 1970|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 7, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Station layout==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=36th Street\n|l1=36 St\n|2=53rd Street\n|l2=53 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=315\n}}\n}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout BMT Fourth Avenue Line|prev2=36th Street|next2=53rd Street}}\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s. The R stops here at all times;<ref name=\"ttr\">{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref> some rush-hour W trains stop here in the peak direction;<ref name=\"ttw\">{{NYCS const|timetable|w}}</ref> and the N stops here during late nights, but uses the center express tracks to bypass the station during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref> The platforms are offset as the northbound platform extends further north than the southbound one.<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook3}}</ref>\n\nColumns run along the entire length of both platforms and are painted dark blue. Every other column has a \"45 Street\" sign on it in black with white text. All are round except for the ones near the staircases to the station's main entrance, which was where the platforms were extended in 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r13.jpg|title=A view down the Bay Ridge-bound side platform at 45 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> These columns are I-beams.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r21.jpg|title=Looking down the Bay Ridge-bound platform at 45 Street, this portion must be part of the area added when the platform was extended since it has I-beams all along it.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=October 1, 2012|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> Since the renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain gray-painted cinderblock tiles. The gray cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r1.jpg|title=A 45 Street platform sign, text and an arrow for the only exit to 45 St painted beneath it.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear|left}}[[File:45th St BMT stair jeh.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Eastern street stair]]\n\n===Exits===\nThe station's main entrance is a [[mezzanine (architecture)|mezzanine]] above the platforms and tracks at the north end. It has two staircases to the Manhattan-bound platform<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r24.jpg|title=Looking across to the offset Manhattan-bound platform and the two staircases it has to the mezzanine|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=October 1, 2012|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> and one to the Bay Ridge-bound one at the extreme south end,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r5.jpg|title=Approaching the single staircase up to street level from the Bay Ridge-bound platform at 45 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> a waiting area that allows a free transfer between directions, [[turnstile]] bank, token booth, and two staircases to the northern corners of 45th Street and 4th Avenue.<ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref> The mezzanine contains some of the original mosaic directional and arrow signs. The one by the staircases to the southbound platform says \"Down Town trains\" while the one by the Manhattan-bound platform staircases says \"Up Town Trains.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r7.jpg|title=A mosaic sign for Up Town trains above a modern To 95 Street R sign at 45 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r9.jpg|title=A Down Town Trains mosaic above a modern Manhattan & Queens R sign on the mezzanine at 45 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe southbound platform formerly had an exit-only at the center that led to 46th Street. Evidence of this includes a gated door on the platform wall and adjacent \"EXIT\" signs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r19.jpg|title=A close up of partially painted over text for the now closed exit to 46 St.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/45r18.jpg|title=A gated door where a high exit turnstile to 46 Street used to leave the Bay Ridge-bound platform from.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The northwest corner exit was closed after it was accidentally destroyed by nearby construction workers. On May 16, 1979, Community Board 7 held a meeting to determine whether residents wanted the entrance closed.<ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26222806/daily_news/|title=Public Hearing|last=|first=|date=May 14, 1979|work=New York Daily News|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The board's chairman cited crime as a reason to close the entrance. The New York City Transit Authority promised to comply with the wish of the board, and the entrance was closed.<ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26223211/daily_news/|title=Express Ideas on BMT Station|last=|first=|date=May 14, 1979|work=New York Daily News|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|45th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:262|BMT 4th Avenue|45th Street}}\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150113014240/http://www.stationreporter.net/rtrain.htm R Train]\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/45r/index.php 45th Street Pictures]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.649322,-74.009721&spn=0,0.013314&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.649393,-74.009652&panoid=xaDl-Fa-Y0P2G9iP_BWMHQ&cbp=12,326.9,,0,9.86 45th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6492729,-74.0095825,3a,75y,98.46h,89.75t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s-dGaQtrQutyc%2FWG3KMnRZW4I%2FAAAAAAAAYWA%2FfSN1j1gWg7AwQffylXaJ01uYxVCM8Jw4QCLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2F-dGaQtrQutyc%2FWG3KMnRZW4I%2FAAAAAAAAYWA%2FfSN1j1gWg7AwQffylXaJ01uYxVCM8Jw4QCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:45th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sunset Park, Brooklyn]]\n", "name_user":