ve}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"alltimesales\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000302112243/http://pc.ign.com/news/11728.html |url=http://pc.ign.com:80/news/11728.html |title=PC Data Top Games of All Time |date=November 1, 1999 |author=IGN Staff |work=[[IGN]] |archivedate=March 2, 2000 |url-status=dead |access-date=May 31, 2018 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/doom-ii |title=DOOM II for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=August 5, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303083653/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/doom-ii |archivedate=March 3, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MC-GBA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/doom-ii |title=Doom II for Game Boy Advance Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MC-X360\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/doom-ii |title=DOOM II for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Allgame-DM2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14065 |work=[[Allgame]] |publisher=[[All Media Guide]] |accessdate=September 26, 2014 |last=House |first=Matthew |title=Doom II - Overview |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114141910/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14065 |archivedate=November 14, 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NG\">{{cite magazine|title=Finals |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=1 |publisher=[[Future US|Imagine Media]] |date=January 1995 |page=94}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MasterLevels\">{{Cite journal |last=D. |first=E. |date=May 1996 |title=Master Levels for Doom II |url=https://archive.org/details/PCPowerplay-001-1996-05/page/n61 |journal=[[PC PowerPlay]] |issue=1 |pages=62}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"macuser\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010221033422/http://macuser.zdnet.com/mu_0396/personal/gameroom.html |url=http://macuser.zdnet.com:80/mu_0396/personal/gameroom.html |title=The Game Room |author=LeVitus, Bob |date=March 1996 |work=[[MacUser]] |archivedate=February 21, 2001 |url-status=dead |access-date=July 23, 2018 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"GR-DM2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/197142-doom-ii/index.html |title=Doom II for PC |publisher=GameRankings |date=1994-09-30 |accessdate=2012-06-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718214652/http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/197142-doom-ii/index.html |archivedate=2012-07-18}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Dragon216\">{{cite journal|title=Eye of the Monitor |author=Cook, David |journal=Dragon |issue=216 |date=April 1995 |pages=63\u201366 |authorlink=David Cook (game designer)}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NextGen-DM2\">{{cite magazine|last=Crawford |first=Chris |title=The Way Games Ought to Be |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=17 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=May 1996 |pages=126\u20137}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"OriginsAward\">{{cite web |url=http://www.originsgames.com/awards/1994 |title=Origins Award Winners (1994) |accessdate=2007-09-18 |publisher=Academy of Adventure Gaming Arts & Design |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070830114223/http://www.originsgames.com/awards/1994  |archivedate=2007-08-30 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{moby game|id=/doom-ii_}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Solar System|Speculative fiction|United States|Video games}}\n{{DOOMgames}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doom 2}}\n[[Category:1994 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:AmigaOS 4 games]]\n[[Category:Amiga 1200 games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled 3DO Interactive Multiplayer games]]\n[[Category:Commercial video games with freely available source code]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:Video games about demons]]\n[[Category:Doom (series)]]\n[[Category:Doom engine games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:DOS games ported to Windows]]\n[[Category:First-person shooters]]\n[[Category:Game Boy Advance games]]\n[[Category:Games commercially released with DOSBox]]\n[[Category:GT Interactive Software games]]\n[[Category:Hell in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Id Software games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Mac OS games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer null modem games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:Origins Award winners]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Science fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Video game sequels]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Robert Prince]]\n[[Category:Video games with 2.5D graphics]]\n[[Category:Video games with digitized sprites]]\n[[Category:Video games with expansion packs]]\n[[Category:Video games with variable translation control]]\n[[Category:Virgin Interactive games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 Live Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Sprite based First-person shooters]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toVideo game port(link changed toPorting#Porting_in_gaming) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doom_II"}
{"title_page": "Olmec hieroglyphs", "text_new": "The [[Olmecs]] were the earliest known major [[Mesoamerica|Mesoamerican]] [[civilization]]. The Olmecs flourished during [[Mesoamerica]]'s [[Mesoamerican chronology|formative period]] (1500 [[Before the Common Era|BCE]] to 400 BCE) in the tropical lowlands of the modern-day Mexican states of [[Veracruz]] and [[Tabasco]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Diehl|first=Richard A.|url=https://archive.org/details/olmecsamericasfi0000dieh/page/9|title=The Olmecs : America's First Civilization|publisher=Thames and Hudson|year=2004|isbn=0-500-28503-9|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/olmecsamericasfi0000dieh/page/9 9\u201325]|authorlink=Richard Diehl}}</ref> The subsequent [[Epi-Olmec culture]] (300 BCE to 250 CE), was a successor culture to the Olmec and featured a full-fledged writing system, the [[Isthmian script|Isthmian (or Epi-Olmec) script]]. \n\nThe existence of a writing system in Middle and Late Olmec periods has been a matter of long-standing debate. Evidence includes the appearance of individual (potential) glyphs as well as the singleton [[Cascajal Block]] that bears a potential text. \n\n=== Cascajal block (approx. 900 BCE) ===\n[[File:Cascajal-text.svg|right|thumb|The 62 glyphs of the [[Cascajal block]]]]\n{{Main|Cascajal Block}}\nIn September 2006, a report published in Science magazine announced the discovery of the Cascajal block, a writing-tablet-sized block of serpentine with 62 characters unlike any yet seen in Mesoamerica. This block was discovered by locals in the Olmec heartland and was dated by the archaeologists to approximately 900 BCE based on other debris. If the authenticity and date can be verified, this will prove to be the earliest writing yet found in Mesoamerica. The symbols on the Cascajal block are unlike those of any other writing system in Mesoamerica, such as in [[Mayan languages]] or [[Isthmian script|Isthmian]], another extinct Mesoamerican script. The Cascajal block is also unusual because the symbols apparently run in horizontal rows and \"there is no strong evidence of overall organization. The sequences appear to be conceived as independent units of information\".<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rodr\u00edguez Mart\u00ednez, Ma. del Carmen|author2=Ponciano Ort\u00edz Ceballos|author3=Michael D. Coe|author3-link=Michael D. Coe|author4=Richard A. Diehl|author5=Stephen D. Houston|author5-link=Stephen D. Houston|author6=Karl A. Taube|author6-link=Karl A. Taube|author7=Alfredo Delgado Calder\u00f3n|date=2006-09-16|title=Oldest Writing in the New World|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/313/5793/1610|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|location=Washington, DC|publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]|volume=313|issue=5793|pages=1610\u20131614|doi=10.1126/science.1131492|oclc=200349481|pmid=16973873}}</ref>\n[[File:San_Andres_Cylinder_Seal_print_1.svg|alt=|left|thumb|375x375px|A rollout of the San Andr\u00e9s cylinder seal, showing the bird possibly \"speaking\" the name \"3 Ajaw\"]]\n\n=== Potential glyphs ===\nIt was long thought that many of the glyphs present on Olmec monumental sculpture, such as those on the so-called \"Ambassador Monument\" ([[La Venta]] Monument 13), represented an early Olmec script. This suspicion was reinforced in 2002 by the announcement of the discovery of [[San Andr\u00e9s (Mesoamerican site)#Indications of an Olmec writing system|similar glyphs]] at [[San Andres (Mesoamerican site)|San Andres]], dated to approx. 650 BCE.<ref>https://science.sciencemag.org/content/298/5600/1984/tab-figures-data</ref> The San Andres glyphs have been interpreted as \"3 Ajaw\" and may represent a direct predecessor of Epi-Olmec writing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pohl|first=Mary E. D.|last2=Pope|first2=Kevin O.|last3=Nagy|first3=Christopher von|date=2002-12-06|title=Olmec Origins of Mesoamerican Writing|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/298/5600/1984|journal=Science|language=en|volume=298|issue=5600|pages=1984\u20131987|doi=10.1126/science.1078474|issn=0036-8075|pmid=12471256}}</ref>  \n\n=== Contemporary potential glyphs ===\nThe Tlatilco cylinder seal dates to the time frame of the Olmec occupation of [[Tlatilco]], and appears to carry a non-pictographic, linear script.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kelley|first=David H.|date=1966-07|title=A Cylinder Seal from Tlatilco|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0002731600095226/type/journal_article|journal=American Antiquity|language=en|volume=31|issue=5Part1|pages=744\u2013746|doi=10.2307/2694503|issn=0002-7316}}</ref> A cylinder seal from [[Chiapa de Corzo (Mesoamerican site)|Chiapa de Corzo]], Mexico, also appears to be an example of an unknown Mesoamerican script. Both have been discussed as potential evidence for Olmec writing as they appeared during a time of Olmec influence.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kelley|first1=David H.|date=1966|title=A Cylinder Seal from Tlatilco|journal=American Antiquity|volume=31|issue=5|pages=744\u201346|doi=10.2307/2694503|jstor=2694503}}</ref>  \n\n[[File:La_Mojarra_Estela_1_(Escritura_superior).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Detail showing glyphs from 2nd century CE [[La Mojarra Stela 1]] currently located at the Museum of Anthropology of Xalapa, Veracruz, Mexico. The left column gives a Long Count date of 8.5.16.9.9, or 162 CE. The other columns are glyphs from the [[Epi-Olmec script]].]]\n\n=== Epi-Olmec or Isthmian script ===\n{{Main|Epi-Olmec script}}\nA small number of artifacts found in the [[Isthmus of Tehuantepec]] show examples of another early Mesoamerican writing system. They can be seen to contain calendric information but are otherwise undeciphered. The longest of these texts are on [[La Mojarra Stela 1]] and the [[Tuxtla Statuette]]. The writing system used is very close to the Maya script, using affixal glyphs and Long Count dates, but is read only in one column at a time as is the Zapotec script. It has been suggested that this Isthmian or [[Epi-Olmec script]] is the direct predecessor of the Maya script, thus giving the Maya script a non-Maya origin. Another artifact with Epi-Olmec script is the Chiapa de Corzo stela which is the oldest monument of the Americas inscribed with its own date: the [[Maya calendar#Long Count|Long Count]] on the stela dates it to 36 BCE.\n\nIn a 1997 paper, John Justeson and Terrence Kaufman put forward a decipherment of Epi-Olmec. The following year, however, their interpretation was disputed by Stephen Houston and [[Michael D. Coe]], who unsuccessfully applied Justeson and Kaufman's decipherment system against epi-Olmec script from the back of a hitherto unknown mask. The matter remains under dispute.\n\n== References ==\n", "text_old": "The [[Olmecs]] were the earliest known major [[Mesoamerica|Mesoamerican]] [[civilization]]. The Olmecs flourished during [[Mesoamerica]]'s [[Mesoamerican chronology|formative period]] (1500 [[Before the Common Era|BCE]] to 400 BCE) in the tropical lowlands of the modern-day Mexican states of [[Veracruz]] and [[Tabasco]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Diehl|first=Richard A.|url=https://archive.org/details/olmecsamericasfi0000dieh/page/9|title=The Olmecs : America's First Civilization|publisher=Thames and Hudson|year=2004|isbn=0-500-28503-9|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/olmecsamericasfi0000dieh/page/9 9\u201325]|authorlink=Richard Diehl}}</ref> The subsequent [[Epi-Olmec culture]] (300 BCE to 250 CE), was a successor culture to the Olmec and featured a full-fledged writing system, the [[Isthmian script|Isthmian (or Epi-Olmec) script]]. \n\nThe existence of a writing system in Middle and Late Olmec periods has been a matter of long-standing debate. Evidence includes the appearance of individual (potential) glyphs as well as the singleton [[Cascajal Block]] that bears a potential text. \n\n=== Cascajal block (approx. 900 BCE) ===\n[[File:Cascajal-text.svg|right|thumb|The 62 glyphs of the [[Cascajal block]]]]\n{{Main|Cascajal Block}}\nIn September 2006, a report published in Science magazine announced the discovery of the Cascajal block, a writing-tablet-sized block of serpentine with 62 characters unlike any yet seen in Mesoamerica. This block was discovered by locals in the Olmec heartland and was dated by the archaeologists to approximately 900 BCE based on other debris. If the authenticity and date can be verified, this will prove to be the earliest writing yet found in Mesoamerica. The symbols on the Cascajal block are unlike those of any other writing system in Mesoamerica, such as in [[Mayan languages]] or [[Isthmian script|Isthmian]], another extinct Mesoamerican script. The Cascajal block is also unusual because the symbols apparently run in horizontal rows and \"there is no strong evidence of overall organization. The sequences appear to be conceived as independent units of information\".<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rodr\u00edguez Mart\u00ednez, Ma. del Carmen|author2=Ponciano Ort\u00edz Ceballos|author3=Michael D. Coe|author3-link=Michael D. Coe|author4=Richard A. Diehl|author5=Stephen D. Houston|author5-link=Stephen D. Houston|author6=Karl A. Taube|author6-link=Karl A. Taube|author7=Alfredo Delgado Calder\u00f3n|date=2006-09-16|title=Oldest Writing in the New World|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/313/5793/1610|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|location=Washington, DC|publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]|volume=313|issue=5793|pages=1610\u20131614|doi=10.1126/science.1131492|oclc=200349481|pmid=16973873}}</ref>\n[[File:San_Andres_Cylinder_Seal_print_1.svg|alt=|left|thumb|375x375px|A rollout of the San Andr\u00e9s cylinder seal, showing the bird possibly \"speaking\" the name \"3 Ajaw\"]]\n\n=== Potential glyphs ===\nIt was long thought that many of the glyphs present on Olmec monumental sculpture, such as those on the so-called \"Ambassador Monument\" ([[La Venta]] Monument 13), represented an early Olmec script. This suspicion was reinforced in 2002 by the announcement of the discovery of [[San Andr\u00e9s (Mesoamerican site)#Indications of an Olmec writing system|similar glyphs]] at [[San Andres (Mesoamerican site)|San Andres]], dated to approx. 650 BCE.<ref>https://science.sciencemag.org/content/298/5600/1984/tab-figures-data</ref> The San Andres glyphs have been interpreted as \"3 Ajaw\" and may represent a direct predecessor of Epi-Olmec writing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pohl|first=Mary E. D.|last2=Pope|first2=Kevin O.|last3=Nagy|first3=Christopher von|date=2002-12-06|title=Olmec Origins of Mesoamerican Writing|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/298/5600/1984|journal=Science|language=en|volume=298|issue=5600|pages=1984\u20131987|doi=10.1126/science.1078474|issn=0036-8075|pmid=12471256}}</ref>  \n\n=== Contemporary potential glyphs ===\nThe Tlatilco cylinder seal dates to the time frame of the Olmec occupation of [[Tlatilco]], and appears to carry a non-pictographic, linear script.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kelley|first=David H.|date=1966-07|title=A Cylinder Seal from Tlatilco|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0002731600095226/type/journal_article|journal=American Antiquity|language=en|volume=31|issue=5Part1|pages=744\u2013746|doi=10.2307/2694503|issn=0002-7316}}</ref> A cylinder seal from [[Chiapa de Corzo (Mesoamerican site)|Chiapa de Corzo]], Mexico, also appears to be an example of an unknown Mesoamerican script. Both have been discussed as potential evidence for Olmec writing as they appeared during a time of Olmec influence.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kelley|first1=David H.|date=1966|title=A Cylinder Seal from Tlatilco|journal=American Antiquity|volume=31|issue=5|pages=744\u201346|doi=10.2307/2694503|jstor=2694503}}</ref>  \n\n[[File:La_Mojarra_Estela_1_(Escritura_superior).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Detail showing glyphs from 2nd century CE [[La Mojarra Stela 1]] currently located at the Museum of Anthropology of Xalapa, Veracruz, Mexico. The left column gives a Long Count date of 8.5.16.9.9, or 162 CE. The other columns are glyphs from the [[Epi-Olmec script]].]]\n\n=== Epi-Olmec or Isthmian script ===\n{{Main|Epi-Olmec script}}\nA small number of artifacts found in the [[Isthmus of Tehuantepec]] show examples of another early Mesoamerican writing system. They can be seen to contain calendric information but are otherwise undeciphered. The longest of these texts are on [[La Mojarra Stela 1]] and the [[Tuxtla Statuette]]. The writing system used is very close to the Maya script, using affixal glyphs and Long Count dates, but is read only in one column at a time as is the Zapotec script. It has been suggested that this Isthmian or [[Epi-Olmec script]] is the direct predecessor of the Maya script, thus giving the Maya script a non-Maya origin. Another artifact with Epi-Olmec script is the Chiapa de Corzo stela which is the oldest monument of the Americas inscribed with its own date: the [[Maya calendar#Long Count|Long Count]] on the stela dates it to 36 BCE.\n\nIn a 1997 paper, John Justeson and Terrence Kaufman put forward a decipherment of Epi-Olmec. The following year, however, their interpretation was disputed by Stephen Houston and [[Michael D. Coe]], who unsuccessfully applied Justeson and Kaufman's decipherment system against epi-Olmec script from the back of a hitherto unknown mask. The matter remains under dispute.\n", "name_user": "Chiarcos", "label": "safe", "comment": "layout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olmec_hieroglyphs"}
{"title_page": "25th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{For|the demolished station actually at 36th Street & Fifth Avenue|36th Street (BMT Fifth Avenue Line)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 25 Street\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = white\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| bg_color_2 = #874F17\n| image = 25th Street BMT Fourth Avenue 1279.JPG\n| image_caption = Southbound platform\n| address = 25th Street &amp; Fourth Avenue<br>Brooklyn, NY 11232<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Greenwood Heights, Brooklyn|Greenwood Heights]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.6605|N|73.998|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth center local\n| service_header = Fourth center local header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small>; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}\n| wifi = yes\n| code = 031\n| passengers = 1,149,469<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -16.3\n| rank = 333<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=Prospect Avenue | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=36th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}'''25th Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at the intersection of 25th Street and Fourth Avenue in [[Greenwood Heights, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[D (New York City Subway service)|D]] and [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] trains also stop here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe 25th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 25th Street started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in May 1912. The station opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The platforms were lengthened in 1925 and again during a renovation in 1968\u20131970.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Construction ===\nThe 25th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":123\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref> The contract for the section of the line that included the 25th Street station, Route 11A3, which extended from 10th Street to 27th Street, was awarded on May 22, 1908, to Tidewater Building Company and Thomas B. Bryson for $2,043,162.31 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=2043162.31|start_year=1908|r=-3}}). The [[New York City Board of Estimate]] approved the contract on October 29, 1909.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53922207/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway To Be Political Issue|date=December 11, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|page=1|language=en}}</ref> Construction on the segment started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in May 1912.<ref name=\":123\"/>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> 25th Street opened on June 22, 1915, as part of an extension of the subway to [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue station|Coney Island]], which included the Fourth Avenue Line north of [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]] as well as the entire [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach Line]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Cudahy | first=Brian J. | title=How We Got to Coney Island: The Development of Mass Transportation in Brooklyn and Kings County | publisher=Fordham University Press | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-8232-2211-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cJGUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA218 | access-date=April 24, 2020 | pages=217-218}}</ref><ref name=\"Station Opening22\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, 25th Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|435|feet|meters}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Legislature|first=New York (State)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ugaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA100&dq=%22union+street%22+LENGTHENING&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8_PLm7tboAhXBhOAKHVx0AzwQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20LENGTHENING&f=false|title=Second Annual Report of the Transit Commission (For the Calendar Year 1922)|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Though the Transit Commission ordered the BMT to lengthen these platforms in September 1923, progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=1926-02-26|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=1926-03-18|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1950s and 1960s ====\n[[File:25th Street BMT Fourth Avenue 1281.JPG|thumb|250px|Original mosaic tiles|alt=|left]]In July 1959, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) announced that it would install [[fluorescent lighting]] at the 25th Street station and five other stations along Fourth Avenue for between $175,000 and $200,000. Bids on the project were to be advertised on August 7, 1959 and completed by fall 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47783394/bay-ridge-home-reporter/|title=Our Subway Stations To Be Brighter|date=1959-07-10|work=Bay Ridge Home Reporter|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 25th Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[Pacific Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Pacific Street]] and [[36th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|36th Street]], including those at 25th Street, on March 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=-HNIAQAAIAAJ&dq=Group+XXX%E2%80%94Broadway-Fourth+Avenue+Line:+pacific+Street,+Union+Street,+9th+Street&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Group+XXX|title=Engineering News-record|date=1969|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref> Funding for the renovation projects came out of the NYCTA's 1969\u20131970 Capital Budget, costing $8,177,890 in total.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c-gxGpL_JNQC&dq=%22Pacific+Street+to+36th+Street+stations%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=10-car|title=Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation|date=1969|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=280, 435, 487|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended,<ref name=\":1\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Lines, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=1970-02-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=Prospect Avenue\n|l1=Prospect Av\n|2=36th Street\n|l2=36 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=315\n}}\n}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IND Fulton Street Line}}\n[[File:25th Street BMT Entrance.JPG|thumb|An entrance to the Manhattan-bound platform]]\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks2\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook}}</ref> The R stops here at all times;<ref name=\"ttr\">{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref> some rush-hour W trains stop here in the peak direction;<ref name=\"ttw\">{{NYCS const|timetable|w}}</ref> and the D and N stop here during late nights, but use the center express tracks to bypass the station during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttd\">{{NYCS const|timetable|d}}</ref><ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref> White tiled curtain walls separate the express tracks from the local tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m7.jpg|title=The Zebra stipes conductors stop boards in the middle of the basically bare Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe platforms have no columns except for a section at the extreme north ends where they were extended in 1970. The ceiling in this area is lower.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=Looking towards the Northern end of the Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street, where there's an extremely low cieling and lots of columns. This is because this part of the station was added later when platforms were extended. |url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m8.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |date=June 5, 2009}}</ref> These columns are I-beams and are painted cream colored.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m9.jpg|title=Another view of the portion of 25 Street's platform that was added later, with its cream colored columns and very low ceiling.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> However, the original trim line is still visible in the fare control areas behind the token booth and [[MetroCard#MetroCard vending machines|MetroCard Vending Machines]]. It is in the standard BMT format with \"25\" number tablets in it at regular intervals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m12.jpg|title=The 25 in the trimline of the station entrance|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> Since the renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain orange-painted cinderblock tiles. The orange cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m2.jpg|title=A 25 Street sign above a painted arrow that points towards the station exit, on an orange portion of the platform wall.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Exits===\nEach platform has a same-level [[fare control]] area in the center. As a result, there is no free transfer between directions. Each fare control area has a [[turnstile]] bank, token booth, and single street stair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m5.jpg|title=Looking out to the fare control area for the Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street. The area is quite small with a single staircase up to the street and a narrow token booth.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The staircase on the Bay Ridge-bound platform goes up to the southwest corner of 25th Street and Fourth Avenue while the one on the Manhattan-bound side goes up to the southeast corner.<ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|25th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:183|BMT 4th Avenue|25th Street}}\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/index.php 25th Street Pictures]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.660522,-73.998091&spn=0,359.986567&z=17&lci=transit&layer=c&cbll=40.660579,-73.99819&panoid=RmbAy4q1QnbFxYOuy9eu1Q&cbp=12,243.18,,0,5 25th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6603546,-73.998291,3a,75y,267.69h,88.94t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s--VDhvpTfYIQ%2FWG3KNcfFOOI%2FAAAAAAAAYWM%2FMXHgP2eDhYYxI31gneZgPl3ZBg-mh0uUACLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh6.googleusercontent.com%2F--VDhvpTfYIQ%2FWG3KNcfFOOI%2FAAAAAAAAYWM%2FMXHgP2eDhYYxI31gneZgPl3ZBg-mh0uUACLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platform from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:25th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{For|the demolished station actually at 36th Street & Fifth Avenue|36th Street (BMT Fifth Avenue Line)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 25 Street\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = white\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| bg_color_2 = #874F17\n| image = 25th Street BMT Fourth Avenue 1279.JPG\n| image_caption = Southbound platform\n| address = 25th Street &amp; Fourth Avenue<br>Brooklyn, NY 11232<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Greenwood Heights, Brooklyn|Greenwood Heights]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.6605|N|73.998|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth center local\n| service_header = Fourth center local header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small>; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}\n| wifi = yes\n| code = 031\n| passengers = 1,149,469<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -16.3\n| rank = 333<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=Prospect Avenue | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=36th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}'''25th Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at the intersection of 25th Street and Fourth Avenue in [[Greenwood Heights, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[D (New York City Subway service)|D]] and [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] trains also stop here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe 25th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 25th Street started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in May 1912. The station opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The platforms were lengthened in 1925 and again during a renovation in 1968\u20131970.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Construction ===\nThe 25th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":123\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref> The contract for the section of the line that included the 25th Street station, Route 11A3, which extended from 10th Street to 27th Street, was awarded on May 22, 1908, to Tidewater Building Company and Thomas B. Bryson for $2,043,162.31 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=2043162.31|start_year=1908|r=-3}}). The [[New York City Board of Estimate]] approved the contract on October 29, 1909.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53922207/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway To Be Political Issue|date=December 11, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|page=1|language=en}}</ref> Construction on the segment started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in May 1912.<ref name=\":123\"/>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> 25th Street opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening22\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, 25th Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|435|feet|meters}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Legislature|first=New York (State)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ugaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA100&dq=%22union+street%22+LENGTHENING&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8_PLm7tboAhXBhOAKHVx0AzwQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20LENGTHENING&f=false|title=Second Annual Report of the Transit Commission (For the Calendar Year 1922)|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}). The BMT had been ordered by the Transit Commission to lengthen these platforms since September 1923.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=1926-02-26|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=1926-03-18|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1950s and 1960s ====\n[[File:25th Street BMT Fourth Avenue 1281.JPG|thumb|250px|Original mosaic tiles|alt=|left]]In July 1959, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) announced that it would install [[fluorescent lighting]] at the 25th Street station and five other stations along Fourth Avenue for between $175,000 and $200,000. Bids on the project were to be advertised on August 7, 1959 and completed by fall 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47783394/bay-ridge-home-reporter/|title=Our Subway Stations To Be Brighter|date=1959-07-10|work=Bay Ridge Home Reporter|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 25th Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[Pacific Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Pacific Street]] and [[36th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|36th Street]], including those at 25th Street, on March 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=-HNIAQAAIAAJ&dq=Group+XXX%E2%80%94Broadway-Fourth+Avenue+Line:+pacific+Street,+Union+Street,+9th+Street&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Group+XXX|title=Engineering News-record|date=1969|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref> Funding for the renovation projects came out of the NYCTA's 1969\u20131970 Capital Budget, costing $8,177,890 in total.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c-gxGpL_JNQC&dq=%22Pacific+Street+to+36th+Street+stations%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=10-car|title=Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation|date=1969|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=280, 435, 487|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended,<ref name=\":1\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Lines, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=1970-02-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=Prospect Avenue\n|l1=Prospect Av\n|2=36th Street\n|l2=36 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=315\n}}\n}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IND Fulton Street Line}}\n[[File:25th Street BMT Entrance.JPG|thumb|An entrance to the Manhattan-bound platform]]\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks2\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook}}</ref> The R stops here at all times;<ref name=\"ttr\">{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref> some rush-hour W trains stop here in the peak direction;<ref name=\"ttw\">{{NYCS const|timetable|w}}</ref> and the D and N stop here during late nights, but use the center express tracks to bypass the station during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttd\">{{NYCS const|timetable|d}}</ref><ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref> White tiled curtain walls separate the express tracks from the local tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m7.jpg|title=The Zebra stipes conductors stop boards in the middle of the basically bare Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe platforms have no columns except for a section at the extreme north ends where they were extended in 1970. The ceiling in this area is lower.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=Looking towards the Northern end of the Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street, where there's an extremely low cieling and lots of columns. This is because this part of the station was added later when platforms were extended. |url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m8.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |date=June 5, 2009}}</ref> These columns are I-beams and are painted cream colored.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m9.jpg|title=Another view of the portion of 25 Street's platform that was added later, with its cream colored columns and very low ceiling.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> However, the original trim line is still visible in the fare control areas behind the token booth and [[MetroCard#MetroCard vending machines|MetroCard Vending Machines]]. It is in the standard BMT format with \"25\" number tablets in it at regular intervals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m12.jpg|title=The 25 in the trimline of the station entrance|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> Since the renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain orange-painted cinderblock tiles. The orange cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m2.jpg|title=A 25 Street sign above a painted arrow that points towards the station exit, on an orange portion of the platform wall.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Exits===\nEach platform has a same-level [[fare control]] area in the center. As a result, there is no free transfer between directions. Each fare control area has a [[turnstile]] bank, token booth, and single street stair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m5.jpg|title=Looking out to the fare control area for the Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street. The area is quite small with a single staircase up to the street and a narrow token booth.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The staircase on the Bay Ridge-bound platform goes up to the southwest corner of 25th Street and Fourth Avenue while the one on the Manhattan-bound side goes up to the southeast corner.<ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|25th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:183|BMT 4th Avenue|25th Street}}\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/index.php 25th Street Pictures]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.660522,-73.998091&spn=0,359.986567&z=17&lci=transit&layer=c&cbll=40.660579,-73.99819&panoid=RmbAy4q1QnbFxYOuy9eu1Q&cbp=12,243.18,,0,5 25th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6603546,-73.998291,3a,75y,267.69h,88.94t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s--VDhvpTfYIQ%2FWG3KNcfFOOI%2FAAAAAAAAYWM%2FMXHgP2eDhYYxI31gneZgPl3ZBg-mh0uUACLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh6.googleusercontent.com%2F--VDhvpTfYIQ%2FWG3KNcfFOOI%2FAAAAAAAAYWM%2FMXHgP2eDhYYxI31gneZgPl3ZBg-mh0uUACLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platform from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:25th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/25th_Street_station_(BMT_Fourth_Avenue_Line)"}
